ut which in essence were contrary to Jewish interests. They have not been able to dissociate their needs--religious, spiritual, communal, political--from those of African Americans, and have therefore acted in ways which have threatened their own cultural vitality. Avoiding the focus on Black victimization and white racism that often infuses work on Blacks and Jews, Forman emphasizes the complexities inherent in one distinct white ethnic group's involvement in America's racial dilemma.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aLiberalism. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311071692440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814728901.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814728901zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814728901/original  a978-3-11-071692-4 New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA